// Upload sync (regression). A GPU-resident pool the host writes MID-STREAM — after the pool has gone resident
// — must be refreshed on the device before the next GPU read, via a derived `arche_gpu_upload`. The runtime
// uploads a resident buffer only ONCE (at the first dispatch), so a later host write is invisible to the GPU
// without the derived upload → the kernel would read stale VRAM.
//
// Trace: seed 1 → inc → 2 → inc → 3 (resident) → poke resets P to 100 on the CPU → inc reads 100 → 101 →
// show. Correct = 101. Without the upload, the 3rd inc reads the stale device value 3 → 4. `make
// test-upload-resident` proves the derived upload is load-bearing on a device (101 with it, stale 4 under
// ARCHE_COH_NO_UPLOAD). On the CPU (this RUN, no --gpu) there is no residency and the value is 101 anyway.
// RUN: %arche build -o %t %s && %t | grep -qF "g=101"
#import { fmt }
g :: float;
P :: arche { g }
[8]P(8);

seed :: system { P.g = { 1.0 }; }

@gpu
inc :: map (query { g }) (g) {
  g = g + 1.0;
}

poke :: system { P.g = { 100.0 }; }

show :: system eff {
  fmt.printf("g=%.0f\n", P.g[0]);
}

#run seq({ seed, inc, inc, poke, inc, show })
